%N A394037 Rectangular array, read by descending antidiagonals: denominators in the best approximating array to the golden ratio, phi (A001622). See Comments.
%C A394037 Let Q = {a/b: gcd(a,b)=1, a>0, b>0}; i.e., the positive rationals, reduced to lowest terms, and let x be a positive irrational number. For any dense subset S of Q, a sequence of fractions a(n)/b(n) in S is the S-best approximating sequence if it satisfies these three conditions for all k>=1:
%C A394037   (1) |a(k)/b(k) - x| > |a(k+1)/b(k+1) - x|
%C A394037   (2) b(k) < b(k+1)
%C A394037   (3) if b(k) < v < b(k+1) for some u/v in S, then u/v is not between a(k)/b(k) and a(k+1)/b(k+1).
%C A394037 Define the best approximating array to x by rows, r(n,k), for k>=1, as follows:
%C A394037 Row 1: With S = Q, put r(1,1) = a(1)/b(1), where a(1) = round(x) and b(1)=1. The terms r(1,k) are then uniquely determined by conditions (1), (2), (3). Note that row 1 consists of the convergents to x.
%C A394037 Rows n>=2: With S = (Q after deleting all fractions in rows 1,2,...,n-1), let r(n,1) = the fraction a/b in S that is nearest x and has least denominator b that is new; i.e., a/b is not in the first n-1 rows. The terms of row (r(n,k)) are uniquely determined by (1), (2), (3).
%C A394037 Every row and every column converges to x.
%e A394037 Corner of approximating array:
%e A394037     2/1     3/2     5/3     8/5    13/8    21/13   34/21   55/34   89/55
